04865nam a22008655i 9780674333864DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20131978mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806743338647 a10.4159/harvard.97806743338642doi  a(DE-B1597)248392  a(OCoLC)979575665  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aPA4167 7aHIS0020102bisacsh04a883/.011 aFinley, Jr., John H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHomer's Odyssey /cJohn H. Finley, Jr.  aReprint 2013 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2013] 4c©1978  a1 online resource (244 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- t1. Penelope -- t2. Characterization and Theme -- t3. Origins of the Tales of Travel -- t4. Ogygia and Scheria -- t5. Odysseus’ Tale -- t6. Telemachus -- t7. The Beggar -- t8. Reunion -- t9. Conclusion -- tAppendix I. The Second Nekyia -- tAppendix II. The Reunion at the Farm -- tReferences -- tIndex of Passages -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is the long-awaited work on Homer's Odyssey by one of our foremost teachers and scholars of the classics--John H. Finley, Jr. Already, generations of students at Harvard have benefited from his knowledge and understanding of Homer's words and world. Now his thoughts on the Odyssey are woven together in this remarkable volume. Finley begins by arguing the unity of design in the Odyssey, and shows the connection between the actions of three main characters: Telemachus' maturity brings Penelope to her long-delayed decision for remarriage, which, by producing the bow as marriage-test, gives the unknown Odysseus his means of success against the suitors. Finley also suggests that the poem is a kind of half-divine comedy. About an older man's glad return, it contrasts to the Iliad's story of young man's death far from home. It is a comedy to the Iliad's tragedy and, like Shakespeare's Tempest, it brings the absent king to knowledge which, though initially unwelcome, proves his and others' happiness. Throughout his book, Finley applies a lifetime's learning to a work that is universally recognized as one of the highest achievements of our civilization. At a time when Homer is in danger of being swallowed by specialists, it is important to recognize and uphold the poet's basic concern for life and myth and legend. Such sympathy combined with knowledge is Finley's fine achievement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEpic poetry, GreekxHistory and criticism. 0aEpic poetry, Greek. 0aFolklore in literature. 0aFolklore. 0aGriechische Literatur. 0aMärchen. 0aOdyssea (Homerus). 0aOdysseus (Greek mythology) in literature. 4aHomer. Odyssey. 4aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical. 4aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Greece.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: World History eBook Packagez9783110353563oZDB-23-HWH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067433385740uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067433386440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674333864423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674333864/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-HCO